\begin{itemize}
\item A better title would be great. I also like the idea of having a bolded sentence driving home the point in each section.
\item \sout{We should list a few key ``buzzwords'' that should be hit (if not in the abstract, somewhere within the body of the application). E.g.: big data (heh), ...}
\item \sout{Actually count the planetary systems that were d/c with Systemic}
\item \sout{Add some passing reference to Meschiari et al., 2011 (discovery w/ citizen enthusiast)} \rarr{} in the ``relevant works'' section of bibliography
\item \sout{I would like to do a quantitative comparison between the reach within the literature of a popular code and Systemic. E.g. between '09 and '13, 5864 papers containing the keywords exoplanet/extrasolar planet were published; 55 cited Systemic. Is this a comparable reach to, say, Gadget2, once you normalize for all papers about Dark matter simulations/Galaxy formation/LSS formation/etc.?} \rarr{} in white paper
\item \sout{If we use LSST as a potential use case, then have an order-of-magnitude estimate of the amount of data produced (petabytes?). Also mention that LSST will have community access \& computing resources dedicated to the community access.}
\item Any nod to Kepler?
\item Change unusual to ``so unlike our own''
\end{itemize}
